  <brief_title>Ambulatory Assessment of Motor State in Patients With Parkinson's Disease in Real Daily Life</brief_title>
  <sponsors>
    <lead_sponsor>
      <agency>Radboud University</agency>
      <agency_class>Other</agency_class>
    </lead_sponsor>
  </sponsors>
  <source>Radboud University</source>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Patients with Parkinson's disease (PD) suffer from motor fluctuations and levodopa induced
      dyskinesia. The prupose of this study is to evaluate the effect of an automatic system to
      assess the motor state of PD patients in real daily life. Movements and postures are assessed
      using 6 accelerometers attached to the the most affected wrist, trunk, both upper legs and
      both upper arms. Patients wear the system for two days and keep an own diary of their motor
      state
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
